    "long_instructions": "A city official is planning the construction of a new bridge and wants to estimate how many cars might cross it in a day.\r\n\r\n✅ <strong>TO DO #1:</strong> In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Simulation.java</code>, write the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">getDailyCars()</code> method. This method should:\r\n\r\n1. Return a random whole number between <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">200</code> and <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">500</code> (inclusive).\r\n\r\n✅ <strong>TO DO #2:</strong> In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">SimulationRunner.java</code>,\r\n\r\n1. Call the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">getDailyCars()</code> method 5 times to simulate traffic for 5 days.\r\n\r\n2. Print the number of cars for each day so it's clear what values were generated.\r\n\r\n3. Calculate the average of the 5 values and print the result.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Use <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">(int)(Math.random() * (max - min + 1)) + min</code> to generate a random number between two values.\r\n</div>\r\n",
